  "text": "User: in an earlier session you suggested running an independant separate linux based server, with an rtx 3070 or 3090. I could use my mac mini to connect to it over local network. This would give us more room for future upgrades. thoughts?\n\nAssistant: I don't have that specific conversation in my persistent memory, but the architecture makes total sense and I'd stand by that recommendation. Here's why:\n\n**Linux + NVIDIA GPU advantages:**\n\n1. **Raw CUDA performance** \u2014 NVIDIA's inference stack (TensorRT, vLLM) is battle-tested and optimized for Linux. You get 2-3x the throughput vs Apple Silicon for the same model size.\n\n2. **VRAM headroom** \u2014 RTX 3090 has 24GB dedicated VRAM. That comfortably runs 30B+ models quantized, or multiple 7B models simultaneously. RTX 3070 has 8GB \u2014 similar to your M2, so less compelling.\n\n3. **Upgrade path** \u2014 Standard PCIe means you can swap in a 4090 (24GB) or eventually a used enterprise card (A100, L40) as they depreciate. Apple Silicon is soldered and fixed.\n\n4. **Cost efficiency** \u2014 Used 3090s run $700-900. A Linux box with a 3090 costs less than a 32GB Mac Studio and outperforms it for inference.\n\n5. **Separation of concerns** \u2014 Mac Mini runs the app, handles UI, orchestrates. Linux box is pure inference muscle. Clean architecture, independent scaling.\n\n**The setup:**\n- Linux server (Ubuntu) running Ollama or vLLM\n- Exposes REST API on local network\n- Mac Mini calls it exactly like it calls Claude API\n- Latency over LAN is negligible (<5ms)\n\n**My recommendation:** RTX 3090 over 3070. The 24GB vs 8GB VRAM is the difference between \"can run one small model\" and \"can run our entire hybrid architecture.\" Worth the extra $200-300.\n\nThis is future-proof infrastructure. Solid call.",
